1
1. Technical Leadership
* Oversee and guide all microbiological testing for food, pharma, water, environmental and surface samples.
* Ensure correct method selection, validation, verification, and adherence to SOPs.
* Troubleshoot complex microbiology issues related to media, contamination, equipment performance, and method execution.
* Approve analytical results, reports, and ensure technical integrity.
* Maintain high proficiency in classical and rapid methods (PCR-based, automated systems, pathogen detection platforms).
2. Operational & Quality Management
* Ensure full compliance with ISO/IEC 17025, FSSAI, USFDA, and other relevant standards.
* Work closely with QA for audits, CAPAs, internal assessments, and method reviews.
* Monitor TAT, workload planning, and resource utilisation.
* Oversee media preparation, sterilisation, culture maintenance, consumables planning, and instrument calibration.
* Maintain strict hygiene, biosafety, and contamination-control protocols.
3. Team Management & Development
* Lead a team of microbiologists, analysts, and technicians; assign daily work and ensure timely completion.
* Conduct training sessions, competency evaluations, and skill-upgradation programs.
* Build a culture of discipline, ownership, and continuous improvement.
* Guide juniors on method interpretation, troubleshooting, and documentation accuracy.
4. Documentation & Reporting
* Ensure all worksheets, observations, logbooks, instrument records, and LIMS entries are complete and compliant.
* Review and approve COAs, microbiology reports, and investigations fr OOS/OOT findings.
* Prepare monthly performance metrics and submit to senior management.
5. Stakeholder Coordination
* Coordinate with Operations, QA, Client Service, Sales and Sample Management teams.
* Participate in client audits, technical meetings, and address technical queries.
